That MCP server was easy to set up but it had some drawbacks.

1. Its tools only give access to a SQL database and although Xperience's SQL implementation details are public, they are not the same as the public, supported .NET API of the product. This means we can query the SQL database for insights but we shouldn't invest too heavily in manipulating data directly through SQL.
2. It [is a Node.js package](https://github.com/mihai-dulgheru/mssql-mcp-node) that is magically added to a project through VS Code's UI, making it difficult to identify and manage as a dependency.
3. It doesn't have any hook points to let developers step in and customize the tools exposed by the server. Additionally, because it's written for Node.js, it's not easily customized by Xperience developers who tend to write more C# than server executed JavaScript.
4. It requires managing a connection string in the `mcp.json` file, which needs to be kept in sync with the connection string for the Xperience application.

Wouldn't it be nice if we could resolve all these issues with one simple solution?
