* [The latest April 2025 release](https://code.visualstudio.com/updates/v1_100#_mcp-support-for-streamable-http) of VS Code (v1.100) or newer, which supports MCP Servers using HTTP streaming.
* Xperience by Kentico - [v30.4.1](https://docs.kentico.com/changelog#hotfix-april-30-2025) or newer. This means the Xperience project you try this with needs to be updated to at least that version.

To get started, follow the [Quick Start instructions](https://github.com/seangwright/xperience-community-mcp-server?tab=readme-ov-file#quick-start) in the repository's `README.md`.

1. Install the NuGet package into your ASP.NET Core application.

 ```powershell
 dotnet add package XperienceCommunity.MCPServer
 ```
2. Once the package is installed, update your Xperience by Kentico application `Program.cs`. You can ensure the MCP Server is only available locally by adding some conditional checks around it.

 If you are concerned about security, the [MCP SDK is being updated](https://github.com/modelcontextprotocol/csharp-sdk/pull/377) to leverage ASP.NET Core Identity's native authentication and authorization.

 ```csharp
 // Program.cs

 // ...

 // Adds the MCP dependencies
 if (builder.Environment.IsDevelopment())
 {
 builder.Services.AddXperienceMCPServer();
 }

 // ...

 // Adds the MCP endpoint
 if (builder.Environment.IsDevelopment())
 {
 app.UseXperienceMCPServer();
 }

 app.Kentico().MapRoutes();

 // ...
 ```
3. Start your Xperience application.
4. Set up your [MCP Server configuration VS Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/copilot/chat/mcp-servers#_enable-mcp-support-in-vs-code)

 ```
 {
 "servers": {
 "xperience-mcp-server": {
 "type": "http",
 "url": "http://localhost:<your-port-here>/xperience-mcp"
 }
 }
 }
 ```

 The scheme, domain, and port come from the `launchSettings.json` file in your ASP.NET Core application because it also runs the MCP Server. The default MCP Server path prefix is `/xperience-mcp`.

 You can use the VS Code command palette to [manage and start your MCP Server](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/copilot/chat/mcp-servers#_managing-tools) or you can click the "Start" action above your server configuration in `mcp.json`.
5. Use the tools exposed by the Xperience Community MCP Server [in agent mode in VS Code](https://code.visualstudio.com/docs/copilot/chat/mcp-servers#_use-mcp-tools-in-agent-mode) with a prompt in GitHub Copilot chat.

 ```text
 Tell me about some of the web page content types in this project
 and a summary of their structure and relationships. 
 For example, let me know if some of these web page content types
 have references to content items of other types
 as part of their field definition.
 ```

That's all you need to do to get started!
